    rationale: "MIRTAZAPINE MECHANISM (NaSSA): UNIQUE multimodal action with NO reuptake inhibition: (1) ALPHA-2 ANTAGONISM (central): Presynaptic alpha-2 autoreceptors normally provide negative feedback limiting NE release. Blocking them → INCREASED NE release. Alpha-2 heteroreceptors on serotonergic neurons also regulate 5-HT release — blocking them → INCREASED 5-HT release. (2) 5-HT2A ANTAGONISM → no sexual dysfunction, may enhance sleep architecture. (3) 5-HT2C ANTAGONISM → appetite stimulation (5-HT2C normally suppresses appetite) + weight gain. (4) 5-HT3 ANTAGONISM → no nausea/GI effects (actually antiemetic). (5) H1 HISTAMINE ANTAGONISM → sedation, appetite stimulation, weight gain. PARADOXICAL DOSE-SEDATION RELATIONSHIP: At 15mg, H1 antagonism predominates → maximum sedation. At 30-45mg, alpha-2 antagonism becomes more significant → increased NE release → noradrenergic ACTIVATION counterbalances histaminergic sedation. Net effect: LESS sedation at higher doses. This is why the 'most sedating' dose of mirtazapine is often the LOWEST dose.",
